<Layout title="Gastrointestinal Assessment – Health Assessment">
  <h1>Gastrointestinal Assessment</h1>
  <p><em>Head-to-Toe Assessment Component · Section 1: Health Assessment</em></p>
  <p>
    The GI assessment evaluates the abdomen and digestive function through inspection,
    auscultation, percussion, and palpation — in that order (auscultation before palpation
    to avoid altering bowel sounds).
  </p>

  <h2 id="bowel-sounds">Bowel Sounds — 4 Quadrants</h2>
  <p>
    Auscultate all four quadrants for a minimum of <strong>60 seconds each</strong>
    before concluding sounds are absent. Use the diaphragm of the stethoscope lightly
    placed on the abdomen.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Finding</th><th>Normal</th><th>Definition &amp; Cause</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Normal</strong></td><td>5–30 sounds/min</td><td>Gurgling; borborygmi (longer gurgles); signify peristalsis</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Hyperactive</strong></td><td>&gt;30 sounds/min</td><td>High-pitched, rushing, tinkling; early bowel obstruction, diarrhea, hunger, post-op return of peristalsis</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Hypoactive</strong></td><td>&lt;5 sounds/min</td><td>Infrequent, soft; post-operative ileus, opioid use, electrolyte imbalances</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Absent</strong></td><td>None in 3–5 min</td><td>Paralytic ileus, peritonitis, mesenteric ischemia — <strong>report promptly</strong></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Quadrant Reference</strong>
    RUQ: liver, gallbladder, part of colon. LUQ: stomach, spleen, pancreas. RLQ: appendix,
    cecum, ascending colon. LLQ: sigmoid colon, descending colon.
  </div>

  <h2 id="tenderness">Abdominal Tenderness</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Always perform auscultation and percussion before palpation</strong> — palpation
    alters bowel sounds and may cause involuntary guarding that interferes with assessment.
  </p>
  <h3>Light Palpation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Depress 1–2 cm in all quadrants, starting away from reported pain.</li>
    <li>Assess for: tenderness, rigidity (involuntary muscle tension), guarding.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Deep Palpation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Depress 4–6 cm to assess organ size and deep tenderness.</li>
    <li><strong>Rebound tenderness (Blumberg's sign):</strong> Slowly depress abdomen then release quickly; pain on release suggests peritoneal irritation (appendicitis, peritonitis).</li>
    <li><strong>Rovsing's sign:</strong> Pressure in LLQ causes pain in RLQ; suggests appendicitis.</li>
    <li><strong>Murphy's sign:</strong> Pain/arrest of inspiration on right subcostal palpation; suggests cholecystitis.</li>
  </ul>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Finding</th><th>Description</th><th>Significance</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Voluntary guarding</strong></td><td>Patient tightens abdominal muscles when hands approach</td><td>Apprehension or discomfort — may be reduced with distraction</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Involuntary guarding (rigidity)</strong></td><td>Board-like hardness that cannot be relaxed</td><td>Peritoneal irritation — urgent finding</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Rebound tenderness</strong></td><td>Worse on release than on compression</td><td>Peritonitis; appendicitis</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="lbm">Last Bowel Movement (LBM)</h2>
  <p>
    Always ask about the patient's last bowel movement as part of the admission and
    ongoing assessment:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> Normal range is 3/day to 3/week. Greater or lesser can be normal for the individual.</li>
    <li><strong>Character:</strong> Use the <strong>Bristol Stool Scale</strong> (Types 1–7): Types 3–4 are ideal; Type 1–2 = constipation; Types 6–7 = diarrhea.</li>
    <li><strong>Color:</strong> Brown (normal); black/tarry (melena — upper GI bleed); bright red (hematochezia — lower GI bleed); clay/pale (bile duct obstruction); green (rapid transit or bile).</li>
    <li><strong>Interventions for no BM &gt;3 days:</strong> Assess for constipation; consider PRN stool softener, laxative, or enema per order.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="nausea-vomiting">Nausea &amp; Vomiting</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Assess onset, frequency, character (bilious, bloody, feculent), amount, and associated factors.</li>
    <li><strong>Hematemesis</strong> (vomiting blood) = upper GI bleed — priority notification.</li>
    <li>Monitor fluid and electrolyte balance (risk of hypokalemia, metabolic alkalosis with persistent vomiting).</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Priority GI Findings to Report</strong>
    Absent bowel sounds, rigid abdomen (board-like), rebound tenderness, bloody stools
    (hematemesis or hematochezia), or severe acute abdominal pain require immediate
    physician notification.
  </div>
</Layout>
